article.headline: Cardinal scores career-high 32 in victory
article.linkText: Warriors defeat Suns, win two in a row
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- The best game of Brian Cardinal's career was even better than his wildest dreams -- and given the way Cardinal has played this season, it probably won't be long before he surpasses them again. Cardinal scored 23 of his career-best 32 points in the first half, and Speedy Claxton had 19 points and a career-high 13 assists in the Golden State Warriors' 110-99 victory over the Phoenix Suns on Wednesday night. Jason Richardson scored 19 points in the Warriors' second straight victory heading into the All-Star break -- but despite Golden State's solid teamwork and Richardson's usual array of dunks, all eyes were on Cardinal. The unassuming fourth-year forward has progressed incredibly quickly since playing only 15 minutes all last season with the Washington Wizards. He played 45 minutes against the Suns in his fourth career start while surpassing his career high in points for the fifth time this season. "I knew I could be a contributor in this league," Cardinal said. "Did I ever foresee that I could score 32 points in the NBA? I have to be honest and say no. It's just a product of my teammates and coaches having faith in me to take advantage of opportunities." It's a bit more than that: Cardinal showcased the emerging dimensions in his game by creating his own shot with increasing confidence. After falling just one point shy of his career high in the first half, he added nine points in the fourth quarter along with plenty of the hustle plays and defense that helped him make the team as a free agent. "You want to go into the break with a positive feeling, and now I think we've definitely done that," Cardinal said. "Everybody has been playing so well the last 10 or 15 games, and that opens up a tremendous opportunity for me, because everybody has to be concentrating on them." Coach Eric Musselman can spend the break concentrating on whether Cardinal should remain in Mike Dunleavy's spot in the starting lineup. Erick Dampier had 12 points and 12 rebounds as Golden State overcame the embarrassing memory of its last home game, when the Warriors scored a record-low two points in the fourth quarter of a loss to Toronto. They stayed tough against the Suns, fending off a late rally with big baskets by Claxton and Richardson. "Mentally, I think the team is in the best state that it's been in the entire year," Musselman said. "We've won six out of nine. I think that's a great state of mind." Amare Stoudemire had a season-high 33 points and nine rebounds for the Suns, who fell behind by 24 points early in their fifth straight loss. Phoenix has lost 11 of 13 overall, dropping six games behind the Los Angeles Clippers for last place in the Western Conference. Despite another dismal outing, Phoenix coach Mike D'Antoni made a bold prediction about the rest of the season. "We have 27 games left, and we're going to be in positive territory," he said. "We're going to have a winning record. That's our goal, and we're going to do it." Richardson, the NBA's two-time slam dunk champion, warmed up for this weekend's defense with a handful of jams. The best was a breathtaking, one-handed rebound dunk over Jahidi White in the first quarter as the Warriors built a 22-point lead while holding Phoenix without a basket for more than six minutes. When the Suns cut the lead to 100-92 on Shawn Marion's 3-pointer with 3:20 left, Richardson and Claxton hit consecutive shots. "We could have done a few more things, but we dug ourselves such a big hole in the first half," Marion said. "They kept hitting shots, and the hole kept getting bigger. We can start over after the break. We've got a clean slate, and we'll try to finish out strong." Marion had 19 points and nine rebounds for the Suns, while Joe Johnson had 14 points on 6-of-18 shooting. Phoenix committed 20 turnovers.

Game notes
Claxton also had a career-high seven steals, while veteran Avery Johnson had four points during valuable reserve minutes as Nick Van Exel remained on the Warriors' bench in uniform, nursing a bruised hip. ... The teams finished their season series tied at two games apiece. ... Soft-spoken Phoenix guard Howard Eisley got a rare technical foul in the fourth quarter for protesting a no-call.
